<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,1170,1449]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
The genus 
<taxonomicName box="[274,395,1170,1196]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Allograpta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[274,395,1170,1196]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Allograpta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with approximately 138 species isfound in all areas (except 
<collectingCountry box="[1069,1186,1170,1196]" name="Antarctica" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Antarctica</collectingCountry>
and the extreme north and south and most of the Palaearctic Region), and the majority of these species occur in the Neotropical region (84 species) (
<bibRefCitation author="Thompson, F. C. &amp; Wirth, W. W. &amp; Sedman, Y. S." box="[302,556,1242,1268]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="1 - 195" refId="ref40951" refString="Thompson, F. C., Wirth, W. W. &amp; Sedman, Y. S. (1976) Family Syrphidae. In: A Catalog of the Diptera of the Americas South of the United States. Museu De Zoologica, Universidade De Sao Paulo, 46, 1 - 195." type="journal article" year="1976">
Thompson 
<emphasis box="[432,490,1242,1268]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">et al.</emphasis>
1976
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Nishida, K. &amp; Rotheray, G. &amp; Thompson, F. C." box="[569,790,1242,1269]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="421 - 436" refId="ref38381" refString="Nishida, K., Rotheray, G. &amp; Thompson, F. C. (2002) First non-predaceous syrphine flower fly (Diptera: Syrphidae): A new leafmining Allograpta from Costa Rica. Studia dipterologia, 9, 421 - 436." type="journal article" year="2002">
Nishida 
<emphasis box="[665,715,1242,1268]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">et al</emphasis>
. 2002
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Mengual, X. &amp; Ruiz, C. &amp; Rojo, S. &amp; Stahls, G. &amp; Thompson, F. C." box="[802,1034,1242,1269]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="1 - 28" refId="ref37916" refString="Mengual, X., Ruiz, C., Rojo, S., Stahls, G. &amp; Thompson, F. C. (2009) A conspectus of the flower fly genus Allograpta (Diptera: Syrphidae) with description of a new subgenus and species. Zootaxa, 2214 (1), 1 - 28. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2214.1.1" type="journal article" year="2009">
Mengual 
<emphasis box="[909,960,1242,1268]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">et al</emphasis>
. 2009
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Betty, J. &amp; Thompson, F. C." box="[1046,1333,1242,1269]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="37 - 43" refId="ref33592" refString="Betty, J. &amp; Thompson, F. C. (2010) Two new remarkable flower flies (Diptera: Syrphidae) from New Zealand. The Weta, 39, 37 - 43." type="journal article" year="2010">Betty &amp; Thompson 2010</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Ramage, T. &amp; Sylvain, C. &amp; Mengual, X." pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="1 - 37" refId="ref39273" refString="Ramage, T., Sylvain, C. &amp; Mengual, X. (2018) Flower flies (Diptera: Syrphidae) of French Polynesia, with the description of two new species. European Journal of Taxonomy, 448, 1 - 37. https: // doi. org / 10.5852 / ejt. 2018.448" type="journal article" year="2018">
Ramage 
<emphasis box="[151,201,1278,1304]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">et al</emphasis>
. 2018
</bibRefCitation>
). These flies show considerable variation in morphological characters, such as colour pattern and head shape. Adult flies are pollinators and flower visitors and the immatures of most species are predators of soft-bodies hemipteran pests (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Rojo, S. &amp; Gilbert, F. &amp; Marcos-Garcia, M. A. &amp; Nieto, J. M. &amp; Mier, M. P." box="[396,573,1350,1377]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" refId="ref39615" refString="Rojo, S., Gilbert, F., Marcos-Garcia, M. A., Nieto, J. M. &amp; Mier, M. P. (2003) A world review of predatory hoverflies (Diptera; Syrphidae: Syrphinae) and their prey. CIBIO ediciones, Alicante, 319 pp." type="book" year="2003">
Rojo 
<emphasis box="[456,504,1350,1376]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">et al</emphasis>
. 2003
</bibRefCitation>
for review of published prey records). Recent studies have revealed that some species are secondarily leaf-miners (
<bibRefCitation author="Nishida, K. &amp; Rotheray, G. &amp; Thompson, F. C." box="[567,792,1386,1413]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="421 - 436" refId="ref38381" refString="Nishida, K., Rotheray, G. &amp; Thompson, F. C. (2002) First non-predaceous syrphine flower fly (Diptera: Syrphidae): A new leafmining Allograpta from Costa Rica. Studia dipterologia, 9, 421 - 436." type="journal article" year="2002">
Nishida 
<emphasis box="[665,716,1386,1412]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">et al</emphasis>
. 2002
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Burt, T. O. &amp; Mengual, X." box="[805,1064,1386,1413]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="19860" refId="ref34183" refString="Burt, T. O. &amp; Mengual, X. (2017) Origin and diversification of hoverflies: a revision of the genera Asarkina and Allobaccha- A BIG 4 Consortium PhD project. Research Ideas and Outcomes, 3, e 19860. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / rio. 3. e 19860" type="journal article" year="2017">Burt &amp; Mengual 2017</bibRefCitation>
), stem-borers (
<bibRefCitation author="Zuijen, M. &amp; Nishida, K." pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="37 - 51" refId="ref42182" refString="Zuijen, M. P van &amp; Nishida, K. (2011) Description of life history and immature stages of phytophagous flower fly, Allograpta zumbadoi Thompson (Diptera: Syrphidae: Syrphinae). Studia dipterologica, 17, 37 - 51." type="journal article" year="2011">Zuijen &amp; Nishida 2011</bibRefCitation>
) or pollen-feeders (
<bibRefCitation author="Weng, J. L. &amp; Rotheray, G. E." box="[427,700,1422,1448]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="245 - 258" refId="ref41820" refString="Weng, J. L. &amp; Rotheray, G. E. (2009) Another non-predaceous syrphine flower fly (Diptera: Syrphidae): pollen feeding in the larva of Allograpta micrura. Studia dipterologica, 15, 245 - 258. [2008]" type="journal article" year="2009">Weng &amp; Rotheray 2009</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
